{"success": true, "message": "Fetched question.", "data": {"showTimer": true, "showAttemptInsight": true, "playSounds": true, "dontShowCorrectAnswerImmediately": false, "_id": "6682bd05ba0e94a3c4025a03", "type": "singleCorrect", "level": 2, "category": null, "approximateTimeRequired": 90, "imageBaseUrl": null, "helperText": null, "source": "", "questionLabels": [], "question": {"text": "In case of isoelectronic species the size of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>\u2013</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>\u00a0</mo><mi>Ne</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math> is affected by:", "image": null}, "options": [{"id": "aHBlm", "text": "Principal quantum number\u00a0<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfenced></math>", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "fGP7f", "text": "None of the factors because their size is the same", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "ac8wT", "text": "Electron-electron interaction in the outer orbitals", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "KlCsG", "text": "Nuclear charge\u00a0<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">z</mi></mfenced></math>", "image": null, "isCorrect": true}], "correctValue": null, "solution": {"text": "<p>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mi>Ne</mi><mo>,</mo><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>all have <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>\u00a0</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>\u00a0</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mn>6</mn></msup></math>configuration. They have different size due to the difference in nuclear charge.</p><p>For isoelectronic species, the more nuclear charges, the less will be the size of the species. The valence electrons will experience a greater attractive force due to the increase in nuclear charge.</p><p>Hence, the size of isoelectronic species - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>\u00a0</mo><mi>Ne</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>\u00a0is affected by nuclear charge <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></mfenced></math>.</p><p>Thus, the ionic size of\u00a0<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>\u00a0is the lowest, and the ionic size of\u00a0<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>\u00a0ion is the highest.</p><p>Hence, the answer is D.</p>", "image": null}, "videoSolution": null, "bucket": "Easy Ques (Board Level)", "concepts": [], "masterId": "MOGJMPYQ19081934", "subject": "Chemistry", "subjects": ["615d70bd9948bc1b21da2b1f"], "chapters": ["615d6fed2b295b085ab6ebac"], "topics": [], "previousYearPapers": [{"_id": "65c4c0c11d30997d3436bb06", "title": "JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 1)", "isVisible": true}], "numericalLowerLimit": null, "numericalUpperLimit": null, "classes": [], "microConcepts": [], "exams": ["615d76b2c52ffa3c944600df"], "isRemoved": false, "cpyqbSubjects": ["615f0cf69476412f48314dac", "616057040283de43c87e3e16", "61bb58281213731910ea0b71", "6160579d0283de43c87e3e1f", "61964f94a5a526011886801e", "61c055f6e8ce0dc8a5c62d34", "61a8a2cce8ce0dc8a5c62d2e", "6160577e0283de43c87e3e1c", "616057210283de43c87e3e19", "629105adee9e3ae00d63352c", "62962075e7f8e9ac4daeafd8", "629f385f263330a77be9fa7e", "629f39e4ac11b26562e0625c", "61964ff3a5a5260118868022", "64d50c263df7f4a7f3017f70", "66b79b89d4b564dfab4f94d0", "678ea9a09cc79e5f592bdc12"